In Chapter III, Holmes deduces that a man seen at 3 Lauriston Gardens was likely a retired sergeant of Marines based on physical clues such as an anchor tattoo and military carriage posture, supported by the letter confirming Enoch J. Drebber's identity as the deceased. This deduction underscores Holmes' analytical skills and contrasts with Scotland Yard detectives who are eager to solve the case but may not fully credit their unofficial colleague. The chapter deepens the mystery surrounding Enoch J. Drebber's death and sets up further investigation into 3 Lauriston Gardens, highlighting Gregson’s findings at the scene which reveal blood-red letters spelling "RACHE" in plastering. Holmes attributes this to a suicide attempt but questions its authenticity due to the unusual placement and writing material. This narrative maintains connections with previous context by reinforcing the tension between Holmes and Scotland Yard detectives while building upon the groundwork established for investigating 3 Lauriston Gardens, underscoring the complexity of the case.

